  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Assessing customer risk profiles\n- Monitoring transactions\n- Maintaining detailed records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying authorities about potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Compliance Programs\n- Implementing anti-money laundering (AML) policies\n- Conducting regular employee training\n- Establishing internal controls\n- Performing ongoing risk assessments\n\n4. Legal Frameworks\n- Adhering to Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Following Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Complying with international anti-money laundering regulations\n\n5. Penalties for Non-Compliance\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential criminal charges\n- Loss of banking licenses\n- Reputational damage\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and help law enforcement track potentially illegal financial activities.",
